 epistemological divide formed by Indian independence in 1947.The book focuses largely on British writers on India with chapters on Kipling, E.M. Forster, John Masters, J.G. Farrell and Paul Scott. A final, comparative chapter traces the issues of narrative and power in the work of two post-independence Indian writers - Khushwant Singh and Rohinton Mistry - and deals with the burden of storytelling in a post-colonial situation still fraught with communal and neo-colonial abuses.This book is an important contribution to our understanding of how narrative fiction can reflect and confirm, but also contest and dismantle discourses of power.Key FeaturesOffers new interpretations of well-known texts and writersSuggests an agenda for studying new and less well-known texts to examine the play of narrative and power more generallyDemonstrates possible relations between narrative technique and those larger narratives which feed into the operation of political powerChallenges exclusivist readings which have often asserted 'the colonial' and 'the post-colonial' to be antithetical and mutually exclusive discursive entities"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAnglo-Indian fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aAnglo-Indian fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aInde dans la littérature. 0aIndic fiction (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aNarration. 0aPouvoir (Sciences sociales) dans la littérature. 0aPower (Social sciences) in literature. 0aRoman anglaisxHistoire et critiquex20e siècle. 0aRoman anglo-indienxHistoire et critiquex20e siècle. 0aRoman de l'Inde (anglais)xHistoire et critique. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part 